---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Cambodia | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in Cambodia. Easy visa, ultra-low costs, Bangkok evacuation, and coverage options for expats 70+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Cambodia"
  subheadline="Cambodia offers the easiest visa in Southeast Asia and rock-bottom costs—but limited healthcare means evacuation to Bangkok is essential planning."
  heroImage="/images/countries/cambodia-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose Cambodia</h2>
  <p>
    Cambodia offers perhaps the easiest long-term stay in Southeast Asia—a retirement visa is available on arrival with minimal requirements. Combined with ultra-low living costs (comfortable retirement possible on $1,000-1,500/month), this makes Cambodia attractive for budget-conscious seniors.
  </p>

  <p>
    Phnom Penh, the capital, offers the best healthcare and most developed expat infrastructure. Siem Reap (near Angkor Wat) attracts culture-seekers with a growing expat community. Sihanoukville and coastal areas offer beach life, though recent Chinese development has changed the character of some areas. Kampot provides a quieter riverside alternative.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Visa:</strong> Retirement visa available on arrival; easiest in SE Asia</li>
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Limited; Bangkok evacuation common for serious care</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of living:</strong> $1,000-1,500/month comfortable lifestyle</li>
      <li><strong>Currency:</strong> US Dollar widely used (alongside Riel)</li>
      <li><strong>Language:</strong> English common in expat areas; Khmer elsewhere</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Cambodia's Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Cambodia's healthcare system is developing but limited. For seniors, understanding these limitations is essential—Bangkok (1 hour flight) is the de facto destination for serious medical needs.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Healthcare in Cambodia</h3>
  <p>
    Private clinics and hospitals in Phnom Penh handle routine care and some emergencies:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Royal Phnom Penh Hospital:</strong> Best equipped; some foreign doctors</li>
    <li><strong>Sunrise Japan Hospital:</strong> Japanese management; good reputation</li>
    <li><strong>Calmette Hospital:</strong> French-founded; adequate facilities</li>
    <li><strong>International SOS Clinic:</strong> Expat-focused; coordinates evacuation</li>
    <li><strong>Naga Clinic:</strong> Good for routine care</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Healthcare costs are very low:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GP consultation:</strong> $20-40</li>
    <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> $40-80</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital day:</strong> $100-250</li>
    <li><strong>Basic surgery:</strong> $1,000-5,000</li>
    <li><strong>Complex procedures:</strong> Usually require Bangkok evacuation</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Healthcare in Siem Reap</h3>
  <p>
    Siem Reap has more limited options. Royal Angkor International Hospital provides basic care, but serious conditions require evacuation to Phnom Penh or Bangkok. Emergency helicopter service to Bangkok exists.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Bangkok as Your Medical Hub</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Many Cambodian expats treat Bangkok as their medical hub. A 1-hour flight away, Bangkok's hospitals (Bumrungrad, Bangkok Hospital) offer world-class care. Routine specialist appointments, elective procedures, and all serious care typically happen in Bangkok. Your insurance should treat Thailand as essential coverage territory.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options for Senior Retirees</h2>
  <p>
    Cambodia has the easiest long-term visa in Southeast Asia—a significant advantage for seniors who want minimal bureaucracy.
  </p>

  <h3>Ordinary Visa (E-Class) - Retirement Extension</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Initial entry:</strong> E-visa or visa on arrival ($35)</li>
    <li><strong>Extension:</strong> ER (retirement) extension available in country</li>
    <li><strong>Requirements:</strong> Age 55+, passport, photos, minimal paperwork</li>
    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 1 year, renewable indefinitely</li>
    <li><strong>Health insurance:</strong> Not required</li>
    <li><strong>Income proof:</strong> Not required</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Process Simplicity</h3>
  <p>
    Unlike Thailand (MM2H), Malaysia (high deposits), or Vietnam (no retirement visa), Cambodia requires:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>No financial proof</li>
    <li>No bank deposits</li>
    <li>No health insurance (though strongly recommended)</li>
    <li>No proof of income</li>
    <li>Just age 55+ and passport</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Long-Stay Visa Fees</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>1-year ER extension:</strong> ~$285-300</li>
    <li><strong>Annual renewal:</strong> Same fee</li>
    <li><strong>Exit/re-entry:</strong> Multi-entry included</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Planning Your Cambodia Retirement?"
    description="Get coverage with Bangkok evacuation—essential for Cambodia."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements for Seniors</h2>
  <p>
    Cambodia doesn't require health insurance for the retirement visa. However, insurance is practically essential given healthcare limitations.
  </p>

  <h3>Why Insurance is Critical</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Limited local healthcare:</strong> Complex care unavailable in Cambodia</li>
    <li><strong>Bangkok evacuation:</strong> Costs $5,000-15,000+ without insurance</li>
    <li><strong>No public option:</strong> No access to Cambodian public healthcare</li>
    <li><strong>Dollar economy:</strong> Medical bills in USD; can add up</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Essential Coverage Elements</h3>
  <p>
    For Cambodia, your insurance must include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Medical evacuation:</strong> Unlimited or high-limit to Bangkok</li>
    <li><strong>Thailand coverage:</strong> You'll likely receive care in Bangkok</li>
    <li><strong>Regional network:</strong> Singapore as backup for complex cases</li>
    <li><strong>Repatriation:</strong> Return to home country if needed</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Recommended Approach</h3>
  <p>
    Most Cambodia expats use international insurance that treats Bangkok as the primary medical destination. Routine care in Cambodia, anything serious in Bangkok. High-deductible plans work well since Cambodian routine care is very cheap.
  </p>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Providers for Cambodia</h2>
  <p>
    These insurers work well for seniors in Cambodia:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Excellent for Cambodia residents. Strong Bangkok network (Bumrungrad direct billing). Evacuation coverage included. Entry up to 74 with lifetime renewal. Regional coverage includes Thailand, Singapore, Vietnam.
  </p>

  <h3>BUPA Global</h3>
  <p>
    Accepts applicants up to 79. Comprehensive worldwide coverage with excellent evacuation. Premium pricing but essential option for seniors 75-79. Strong Bangkok hospital network.
  </p>

  <h3>Forte Insurance (Cambodia Local)</h3>
  <p>
    Leading Cambodian insurer. Affordable basic coverage. Age limits apply (typically 65). Limited for international care but covers Cambodian hospitals. Can supplement with international evacuation policy.
  </p>

  <h3>Pacific Cross</h3>
  <p>
    Regional specialist with good Cambodia/Thailand coverage. Entry up to 65 with renewal to 75. More affordable than global insurers. Direct billing at Cambodian and Bangkok hospitals.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Plans with Bangkok Coverage"
    description="Essential for Cambodia's healthcare reality."
    buttonText="See Options →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs for Cambodia are moderate, and local healthcare is extremely cheap:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Ultra-Low Local Costs</h3>
  <p>
    Cambodian healthcare is remarkably affordable:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GP visit:</strong> $20-40</li>
    <li><strong>Bloodwork:</strong> $30-80</li>
    <li><strong>Dental cleaning:</strong> $15-30</li>
    <li><strong>Prescription medications:</strong> 50-80% less than US</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital day:</strong> $100-250 private room</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>High deductible:</strong> Pay routine care out-of-pocket; insure evacuations</li>
    <li><strong>Regional coverage:</strong> Cambodia + Thailand + Singapore sufficient</li>
    <li><strong>Use local clinics:</strong> International SOS not always needed for routine care</li>
    <li><strong>Bangkok medical tourism:</strong> Fly to Bangkok for elective procedures</li>
    <li><strong>Evacuation-only:</strong> If budget tight, prioritize evacuation coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 1: Routine Care in Phnom Penh</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Bob, 71, needs checkup and medications.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Visits Naga Clinic. Consultation $30, bloodwork $50, 3-month medication $40. Total: $120. Pays out-of-pocket—below any deductible. Quality adequate for routine care.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 2: Minor Surgery in Cambodia</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Carol, 69, needs hernia repair.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Surgery at Royal Phnom Penh Hospital. Total cost $2,800. Cigna Global covers after $2,500 deductible. Quality acceptable; recovery in Cambodia.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 3: Cardiac Event Requiring Bangkok</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Richard, 73, has heart attack in Siem Reap.</p>
      <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Stabilized at Royal Angkor Hospital. Air evacuation to Bumrungrad Bangkok—$12,000. Cardiac surgery in Bangkok—$45,000. Total: $57,000. BUPA Global covers fully. Standard outcome for serious cardiac care.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 4: Elective Procedure Strategy</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Susan, 70, needs cataract surgery.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Rather than local care, flies to Bangkok ($80 flight). Surgery at Bangkok Hospital—$3,500 including 2 nights. Quality assured, modern equipment. Cigna covers after deductible. Many expats use this approach for elective procedures.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 5: Senior Without Proper Insurance</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Tom, 72, has only local Cambodian insurance.</p>
      <p class="text-red-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> When he needs emergency appendectomy with complications, local hospital struggles. Evacuated to Bangkok—pays $8,000 out-of-pocket for evacuation. Bangkok surgery covered by travel insurance he bought last-minute. Close call—never skip evacuation coverage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 6: Ultra-Budget Retirement</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">George, 68, on tight Social Security budget.</p>
      <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Gets Allianz Care ($350/month) with $5,000 deductible. Lives in Kampot on $1,200/month total. Pays routine care out-of-pocket ($30-50/month). Insurance provides Bangkok evacuation security. Budget retirement viable with proper insurance.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is the retirement visa really that easy?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes. Arrive on tourist or e-visa, then extend to ER (retirement) category. Requirements: age 55+, passport, photos, ~$300 fee. No income proof, no bank statements, no health insurance required. Renewable indefinitely. Easiest long-term visa in SE Asia.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How often do people really evacuate to Bangkok?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">For serious conditions, very commonly. Cardiac issues, cancer, complex surgery, stroke—all typically mean Bangkok. Many expats fly to Bangkok for routine specialist appointments too (cardiologist, oncologist). Consider Bangkok your medical backup city, not just emergency evacuation.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">I'm 78—what are my options?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">BUPA Global accepts up to 79. Local Cambodian insurers typically cap at 65. At 78, BUPA Global is your main option. Alternatively, maintain emergency fund ($30,000+) plus evacuation-only policy. Cambodian routine care is cheap enough to self-pay.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Phnom Penh or Siem Reap better for healthcare?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Phnom Penh has better hospitals (Royal Phnom Penh, Sunrise Japan). Siem Reap has limited options—Royal Angkor for basics, evacuation for serious care. If healthcare access is priority, Phnom Penh is safer choice. Siem Reap works if you accept Bangkok as your backup.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I really live on $1,200/month?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes, outside Phnom Penh easily. Siem Reap, Kampot: $400-600 rent, $200 food, $100 utilities, $200 entertainment. Total: $900-1,100. Phnom Penh slightly more. Cambodia uses US dollars, so no exchange rate concerns. Add $300-500/month for insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Cambodia safe for seniors?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Generally yes in expat areas. Petty crime exists (bag snatching). Traffic is chaotic—be careful. Healthcare limitations are the main "safety" concern. Established expat communities in Phnom Penh, Siem Reap, Kampot provide support networks. Many seniors live happily here.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for Cambodia?"
    description="Find coverage with Bangkok evacuation protection."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes. Cambodian visa requirements and healthcare capabilities change. Verify current requirements with Cambodian immigration. Consider connecting with the expat community in your target area and always maintain evacuation coverage.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
